title: For Sale:  Saiga, Converted AK 7.62x39 + ammo + mags
postcontent: Its that time of the year and I need to raise some money for some upcoming projects (boat fixing time) so up for grabs is a Saiga 7.62x39 rifle with mags and ammo. I bought this rifle last year and have exactly 280 rounds through it (+3 rounds from the factory certification). This rifle was bought in the "sporter" config and was converted to the AK style set up as most people recognize it. The rifle is in terrific shape and was cleaned and properly maintained after shooting sessions. When I converted it I blasted off the crummy factory finish and had the gun professionally duracoated. The factory certificate reads 113mm spread at 100 yards but it has tightened since the conversion to ~ 95 or so. This Saiga was the IZ 332 with the regular forend and is all correct Russian manufacture with 24mm threads. The furniture is Ironwood designs "Baltic birch" that finished with shellac for that authentic Russian appearance (the shown photographs of the rifle were ironwood handguards and Bulgarian stock, but does include the ironwood stock) However, the photos do it no justice as it came out really nice looking. Overall, I would say the rifle is 98% due to some wear on the finish from handling. The gun is 8lbs unloaded, has a bullet guide installed, G2 trigger and has preformed flawlessly. I am also including the original furniture, three 30 round polymer mags + a bakelite Izmash 30 round mag and last but not least 720 rounds of non corrosive 123 gr Russian manufacture ammunition. The only caveat about the rifle is since converting it I have been using a rakurs optic so I took off the rear 100-300 meter sporter sight and was going to replace it with a true AK rear sight for authenticity, I have the sight but forgot to order the adjustment bar. The part costs about 2 dollars and snaps right in so it shouldn't be too big of a deal. This rifle is nice, with the accessories and ammo I feel that 700 is a fair deal so I am sticking to 700$ firm. I would PREFER a face to face deal, BUT I will ship but you have to cover costs for the ammo and gun + Paypal fee of . If interested please Email me at [email]REDACTED[/email]

Cost: $100 per person. Payment methods are: Cash, Check, or Money Order. Send deposit of $20 in Check or Money Order to: Keystone Firearms Academy, LLC. 6 Miller Ave. New Castle, Pa 16101

 Class size is limited

To sign up for the class: Call: 724-698-6179 OR E-mail: rogers_inc_2011@yahoo.com

Course requirements: Students must be a MINIMUM of 21 years old and previously completed either the NRA Basic Pistol Shooting Course OR an equivalent State CCW Permit Course. Students MUST provide proof of shooting experience prior to the start of the course.
Students are to bring: a defensive caliber handgun – NO Derringers; a minimum of 250 rounds of ammunition; Eye and Ear protection; Holster and at least THREE spare Magazines for your pistol; Notebook and Pen or Pencil for taking notes; Appropriate clothing for current weather conditions (NO open toed shoes); Personal food and drinks.
Description: This course is at least eight hours long and teaches the basic knowledge, skills and attitude essential to the safe and efficient use of a handgun for the protection of self and family and to provide information on the law-abiding individual’s right to self-defense. Students will learn basic defensive shooting skills; shooting from strong/weak sides using cover and standing/kneeling positions; strategies for home safety and responding to a violent confrontation; firearms and the law; how to choose a handgun for self-defense; and continued opportunities for skill development.
Participants should expect to shoot a minimum of approximately 240 rounds of ammunition.

title: For Sale:  Siamese (Thai) type 45 (1903) Mauser bayonet
postcontent:
Bayonets of this sort were produced from 1903 to 1908, in the Imperial Japanese Army Arsenal at Tokyo.

The ricasso, in Siamese characters, reads "RS121," which refers to the year Rattanakosin Sok 121, the 121st year of the Rattanakosin Era, which began in 1782 with the founding of Bangkok. The date equates to 1903 on the Gregorian calendar.

The serial number appears on the pommel, also in Thai script. 

This bayonet is in very good, rust free condition for being over 100 years old.  

A rare bayonet and tough to find for that collection of yours.

I will ship to anywhere in the lower 48 states for $12.00

Email me if you are interested.

First off the action and barrel are only Krylon tan camo. The surface had become rough with patina, so I sanded it smooth with steel wool. Leaving the blue and spray painted it, Wipe it off in 5 mins with any walmart solvent. 

Stock, It's  not nearly that yellow in real life.it's two shades of tan. It was painted two layers of acrylic paint the added about 5 coats of polyurethane It looks like skulls close up but 5ft away it looks like British desert DPM camo

If your buying for your kid. I also have a 1970's wood US Army footlocker painted in the same exact skull pattern I will sell for a $100 Every young Zombie Hunter needs a hope (you don't die) chest to store his lethal tools in.

title: For Sale:  Sold - Rossi Overland Coach Gun, External Hammers, 20 Gauge
postcontent:
Sold

This is a 20 gauge Rossi Overland Coach Gun, external hammers, 20" barrels, in excellent condition. The bores show absolutely no sign of being fired, and I can see any indication on the breech face, hammers, or firing pins. I believe it to be unfired. There are a couple of minor bruises in the wood, but certainly nothing to worry about. Has the original Rossi butt plate. The 20 gauge Rossis are really neat because instead of just putting 20 gauge barrels on the 12 gauge frame, the frame is proportionally smaller. In one photo I show this gun compared to my 12 gauge gun so you can see the difference. The 12 gauge is on the top in the photo.

I have lots of photos so you can see the details. Send me a note and I'll send you the link to them.

These older Rossis are the perfect Cowboy Action shotgun because they don't have the extra, unnecessary and annoying, crossbolt safety, and they work great. This one is especially nice.
